				<pubDate>Wed, 04 Nov 2015 05:08:33 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Qojoc</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2328589</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <blockquote> <p>Object appears to posses a &quot;negative density&quot; (i.e. when object is submerged in a tank of water, the water level will drop, but the object will not take on water)</p> </blockquote> <p>Shouldn't this be negative <strong>volume</strong>? 1&#160;cm<sup>3</sup> of wood displaces the same amount of water as 1&#160;cm<sup>3</sup> of lead, even though the density is different. Besides that, I'd say it is interesting enough to warrant an upvote.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
